The provided Kotlin code violates the **Single Responsibility Principle (SRP)**. 

Here's why:

- The `NotificationService` class is responsible for handling different types of email notifications (`sendNotification`, `sendWelcomeEmail`, and `sendPasswordResetEmail`). This means it has multiple reasons to change, which goes against the Single Responsibility Principle. Ideally, each type of notification should be handled by a separate class or service.

To adhere to SRP, you could refactor the code into different classes for handling different types of notifications:

```kotlin
interface EmailService {
    fun sendEmail(to: String, subject: String, body: String)
}

class GmailService : EmailService {
    override fun sendEmail(to: String, subject: String, body: String) {
        println("Connecting to Gmail SMTP...")
        println("Authenticating with OAuth2...")
        println("Sending email via Gmail: $subject")
    }
}

class OutlookService : EmailService {
    override fun sendEmail(to: String, subject: String, body: String) {
        println("Connecting to Outlook SMTP...")
        println("Authenticating with Exchange...")
        println("Sending email via Outlook: $subject")
    }
}

abstract class NotificationSender(private val emailService: EmailService) {
    abstract fun send(to: String)
}

class GeneralNotificationSender(emailService: EmailService, private val message: String) : NotificationSender(emailService) {
    override fun send(to: String) {
        emailService.sendEmail(to, "Notification", message)
    }
}

class WelcomeNotificationSender(emailService: EmailService, private val username: String) : NotificationSender(emailService) {
    override fun send(to: String) {
        val welcomeMessage = "Welcome $username! Thanks for joining our platform."
        emailService.sendEmail(to, "Welcome!", welcomeMessage)
    }
}

class PasswordResetNotificationSender(emailService: EmailService, private val resetToken: String) : NotificationSender(emailService) {
    override fun send(to: String) {
        val resetMessage = "Click here to reset your password: /reset?token=$resetToken"
        emailService.sendEmail(to, "Password Reset", resetMessage)
    }
}
```

In this refactored code:
- `NotificationService` is replaced by multiple classes (`GeneralNotificationSender`, `WelcomeNotificationSender`, and `PasswordResetNotificationSender`) each responsible for a single type of notification.
- The `EmailService` interface abstracts the email sending functionality, allowing different implementations like `GmailService` and `OutlookService`.

This way, each class has only one reason to change, adhering to the Single Responsibility Principle.

